How to catch the source of the error?

```
var ContractFactory = function (eth, abi) {
    this.eth = eth;
    this.abi = abi;

    this.new.getData = this.getData.bind(this);
};
```

`this.new.getData` is a member of the ContractFactory prototype and not of a ContractFactory instance. This is because `this.new` is not resolved to an instance, but is resolved through the prototype chain of ContractFactory.prototype. 

Therefore this.new.getData will always refer to the getData method of the last ContractFactory instance created because we are assigning it to the ContractFactory.prototype which is shared by all instances.

Hello, I'm too lazy to fork this repo, but I fixed your fromAscii and toAscii functions
Your from Ascii completely ignores the padding.
Your to Asciii returns weird, ugly characters at the end of the result.

``` js
fromAscii = function(str, padding) {
    var hex = '0x';
    for (var i = 0; i < str.length; i++) {
        var code = str.charCodeAt(i);
        var n = code.toString(16);
        hex += n.length < 2 ? '0' + n : n;
    }
    return hex + '0'.repeat(padding*2 - hex.length + 2);
};

toAscii = function(hex) {
    var str = '',
        i = 0,
        l = hex.length;
    if (hex.substring(0, 2) === '0x') {
        i = 2;
    }
    for (; i < l; i+=2) {
        var code = parseInt(hex.substr(i, 2), 16);
        if (code === 0) continue; // this is added
        str += String.fromCharCode(code);
    }
    return str;
};
```

Hope this helps.

